The nervous system

  • The nervous system has two major anatomical subdivisions
    • Central nervous system (CNS)
      • Comprises of the brain and spinal cord
    • Peripheral nervous system (PNS)
      • Comprises of everything else through the body
      • Often subdivided into sensory division and motor division
  • The nervous system maintains homeostasis by
    • Receiving information about the environment
    • Transmits this information CNS where it is processed
    • The CNS issues commands to carry out the response
    • Corresponds to three functional classes of neurons
      • Sensory (afferent) neuronsthat detect stimuli (light, heat, pressure, chemical,etc)
      • Interneuronsthat lie entirely in the CNS
      • Motor (efferent) neuronssend signals to effectors (muscle, glands,etc)

Figure 12.1

Structure of a neuron

  • Major components of most neurons
    • Dendrites
      • Primary site receiving input
    • Soma
      • Contains the nucleus and produces all proteinsetc
    • Axon hillock/Axon initial segment
      • Where an action potential is initiated
    • Axon
      • Rapid conduction of nerve signals
    • Axon terminal
      • Forms a junction/synapse with the next cell

Structure of a neuron

  • There is a huge variety of neuronal structures

Glial cells

  • Neuroglia of CNS
    • Oligodendrocytes
      • Form myelin in the brain and spinal cord
    • Ependymal cells
      • Secrete and circulate cerebrospinal fluid
    • Microglia
      • Phagocytize and destroy dead and foreign material
    • Astrocytes
      • Form a supportive network, nourish and stimulate the neurons
  • Neuroglia of PNS
    • Schwann cells
      • Form myelin
    • Satellite cells
      • Provide electrical insulation and regulate environment of somas in ganglia

Figure 12.6

Resting membrane potential

  • Resting membrane potential (RMP) is the charged difference across the plasma membrane
    • Due to different concentrations of charged particles
  • Typically-70 millivolts (mV)
    • Negative value indicates more negatively charged particles on the inside of the membrane
  • RMP results from a combination of factors
    • The diffusion of ions down their concentration gradient
    • Selective permeability of the membrane
    • The electrical attraction of cation and anions

Resting membrane potential

  • Potassium ions have the largest influence on RMP
    • Due to the membrane being more permeable to potassium than other ions
  • Sodium diffuses into the cell
  • The sodium-potassium pump
    • Works continuously to maintain RMP
    • Requires ATP

Local potentials

  • Stimulation of a neuron causes localdisturbances in membrane potential
    • Occurs in the dendrites and soma
  • Local potentials have the followingproperties:
    • Maybe positive or negative
    • Graded (proportional to stimulusstrength)
    • Reversible (can return to RMP)
    • Local and Decremental (signal growsweaker with distance)

Definition of depolarisation, repolarisation and hyperpolarisation

Silverthorn, Human Physiology

Action potential

  • An action potential is a rapid up-and-down shift in voltage across the membrane
  • Occur when an excitatory local potential spreads all the way to the trigger zone (at the axonhillock/axon initial segment) and is strong enough to open voltage-gated channels

Action Potential

Figure 12.14

  1. A local current depolarises the membrane
  2. The local potential must reach threshold to open voltage-gated channels
  3. Voltage-gated sodium channels and voltage-gatedpotassium channels are activated. Voltage-gated sodiumchannels are very quick to open, causing a depolarisation(positive feedback loop). Voltage-gated potassiumchannels open slowly.
  4. Sodium channels are inactivated and begin closing, sodiuminflow ceases. Potassium channels are now fully open.
  5. Potassium ions exit the cell, repolarising the membrane.
  6. Potassium channels stay open longer than sodiumchannels, producing a hyperpolarisation.
  7. Membrane potential gradually returns to RMP due tosodium diffusion

Action Potential

  • Properties of an action potential
    • All-or-nothing
      • If threshold is reached, an action potential occurs. If below threshold, no action potential. They arenot graded to stimulus strength.
    • Non-decremental
      • Action potentials dont get weaker with distance
    • Irreversible
      • If a neuron reaches threshold, an action potential goes to completion
  • Compare to the local potential which is graded, decremental and reversible.

Action Potential: Refractory period

  • The refractory period occurs immediately after an actionpotential and is a period of resistance to re-stimulation
  • The refractory period can be divided into two phases
    • Absolute refractory period
      • No stimulus of any strength will cause an actionpotential
      • Due to the sodium channels being open or in theinactive state
    • Relative refractory period
      • A large/strong stimulus can cause an actionpotential
      • Potassium channels are still open, so if a newstimulus open sodium channels, potassium willmove out of the cell opposing the effect of thestimulus

Conduction of an action potential

  • Local current flow depolarisesadjacent membrane
    • Results in the activation ofvoltage-gated channels
  • Nerve signal moves in onedirection due to the refractorymembrane

Figure 12.16

Myelinated Fibres and Saltatory Conduction

  • Produces a dramatic increase in speed ofpropagation for the nerve signal
    • Myelin decreases the leakage of sodiumout of the axon
    • Myelin creates a greater separation ofICF and ECF, allowing sodium ions tomove more freely in the axon

Figure 12.18

Synapses

  • When an action potential reaches the axon terminal,usually it will release a neurotransmitter that stimulatesthe target cell
    • The space between the axon terminal and target cell iscalled the synaptic cleft
    • The collection of the axon terminal, synaptic cleft andtarget cell is called a synapse
      • We have already studied one type of synapse, theneuromuscular junction

Neurotransmitters

  • Neurotransmitters are molecules that are synthesized by a neuron, released by an action potential, and,have an effect on the target cell
  • There are a huge number of neurotransmitters and even larger number of receptors (and subtypes ofreceptors)
    • Some examples are
      • Acetylcholine
      • Amino acids such as glutamate and gamma aminobutyric acid (GABA)
      • Monoamines such as adrenaline, noradrenaline, dopamine, serotonin and histamine
      • Gases such as nitric oxide and carbon monoxide
      • Neuropeptides such as cholecystokinin (CCK) and endorphins

Neural integration

How does a neuron decide whether or not to generate action potentials?

  • Recall that local potentials in the dendrites and soma need to depolarise the trigger zone to threshold togenerate an action potential
    • These local potentials are called post-synaptic potentials when the dendrites or soma have receivedsynaptic input
      • They graded, decremental and reversible

Neural integration: summation

  • Summation of graded potentials
    • Summation (a negative potential will reverse the effects of a positive potential)
    • Spatial summation (graded potentials are decremental)
